# Folder Structure

```
src/
├── features/
│   └── <feature>/                    # e.g. search/, books/, scrape/
│       ├── <feature>.types.ts        # TypeScript types + Zod schemas/models
│       ├── <feature>.service.ts      # Business logic only
│       ├── <feature>.repository.ts   # DB, cache, and storage queries
│       ├── <feature>.controller.ts   # Request handling: params, body, response — exports FeatureController object
│       └── <feature>.routes.ts       # Express endpoints via TypedRouter
├── infra/
│   └── <service>/                    # e.g. redis/, mongo/
│       ├── <service>.client.ts       # Client connection/setup
│       └── <service>.service.ts      # Optional wrapper/helpers
├── middleware/                        # Express middleware
├── errors/
│   └── errors.ts                     # Named error classes
├── utils/                             # Shared utilities
├── types/                             # Shared types, .d.ts files, declared namespaces
├── configs/                           # Configuration files
├── logger/
│   └── logger.ts
├── app.ts                             # Express app setup, middleware, route mounting
└── server.ts                          # Server listen + graceful shutdown only
```

## Feature Modules

Each feature folder is self-contained with consistent file naming:

```typescript
// features/books/books.routes.ts
const BookRouter = TypedRouter(express.Router());

BookRouter.get("/", {
  request: GetBooksRequestSchema,
  response: GetBooksResponseSchema,
}, BookController.getBooks);
```

- **routes** → defines endpoints, delegates to controller
- **controller** → exports a single named object (e.g. `BookController`), handles req/res lifecycle, calls service. Methods are passed directly to routes.
- **service** → pure business logic, calls repository
- **repository** → all persistence (DB queries, cache reads/writes)
- **types** → Zod schemas and inferred TypeScript types for the feature

## app.ts vs server.ts

- `app.ts` — creates `const app = express()`, registers middleware, mounts routers, exports `app`
- `server.ts` — imports `app`, calls `app.listen()`, handles `SIGTERM`/`SIGINT` shutdown

## Infra

Third-party integrations (Redis, Mongo, etc.) go in `src/infra/<name>/`. Keep client setup in `<name>.client.ts`. Add `<name>.service.ts` only if the integration needs shared helper logic.

## Standalone Domains

Any module with its own request logic, parsing, or external API integration (e.g. Facebook marketplace requests) should be extracted into its own feature folder following the same controller → service → repository pattern.
